<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="377" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1835,2043]" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1835,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The male imago of 
<taxonomicName box="[495,602,1837,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[495,602,1837,1862]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Bessierus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from all other genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1247,1836,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Leptophlebiidae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: (1) fork of vein MA of forewing asymmetrical (
<figureCitation box="[990,1081,1872,1898]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); (2) vein ICu1 attached to vein CuA by a cross vein, and vein ICu2 attached at base to vein ICu1 by a cross vein; (3) hind wings absent; (4) tarsal claws of a pair dissimilar, one apically hooked, the other blunt (
<figureCitation box="[884,974,1944,1970]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
); (5) forceps sockets fused (
<figureCitation box="[1298,1371,1944,1970]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Figs 2</figureCitation>
C-D); penes widely divided in apical 2/3, apex of each penis lobe with a laterally orientated broad projection (
<figureCitation box="[1301,1371,1980,2006]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Figs 2</figureCitation>
C-D); (7) forceps segment 1 smoothly roundly, broadened in basal 1/3 (
<figureCitation box="[880,962,2016,2043]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="377">Fig.2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="379" pageId="3" pageNumber="378" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,556,152,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">Description of the male imago</emphasis>
(in alcohol). Length of body 2.9 – 3.0 mm, forewing length 3.0- 
<quantity box="[1278,1367,153,179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="378" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
. Head (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,188,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1957,1982]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,272,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[194,1393,272,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, head, d.v.; B, head, l.v.; C, habitus, d.v.; D, habitus, l.v. d.v.= dorsal view; l.v.=lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460232/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">Figs 3</figureCitation>
A-B): Eyes meet on meson of head (
<figureCitation box="[641,731,188,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1957,1982]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,272,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[194,1393,272,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, head, d.v.; B, head, l.v.; C, habitus, d.v.; D, habitus, l.v. d.v.= dorsal view; l.v.=lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460232/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
), lower portion of eyes approximately 4/5 length of upper portion (
<figureCitation box="[210,298,224,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1957,1982]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,272,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[194,1393,272,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, head, d.v.; B, head, l.v.; C, habitus, d.v.; D, habitus, l.v. d.v.= dorsal view; l.v.=lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460232/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460232" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3460232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460232/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="378" startId="3.[151,250,1957,1982]" targetBox="[194,1393,272,1869]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1957,2018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,272,1957,1982]" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">FIGURE 3</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[287,466,1958,1982]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="378" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="doloris">
<emphasis box="[287,466,1958,1982]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="378">
Bessierus 
<taxonomicName box="[394,466,1958,1982]" pageId="3" pageNumber="378" rank="species" species="doloris">doloris</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, male imago. A, head, d.v.; B, head, l.v.; C, habitus, d.v.; D, habitus, l.v. d.v.= dorsal view; l.v.=lateral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis box="[199,267,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Wings</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[286,377,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1247,1272]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,673,1220]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[416,1172,669,1223]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of distribution showing collecting sites in French Guiana and present distribution of Bessierus doloris. Round- ed sites were plotted according the indications of Thomas et al., 2000." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460228" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460228/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Maximum width of forewing is 1/3 of maximum length of forewing; vein Rs of forewing forked 1/5 of distance from base to margin; vein MA forked a little more 1/2 of distance from base to margin, fork asymmetrical, distal portion of vein MA not sagged posteriorly; vein MP forked 3/8 of distance from base to margin, fork symmetrical, distal portion of vein not sagged posteriorly; vein ICu1 attached to vein CuA by a cross vein, and vein ICu2 attached at base to vein ICu1 by a cross vein. Hind wings absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis box="[199,252,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Legs</emphasis>
. Ratio of segments of male forelegs, 0.42:1.0 (
<quantity box="[794,903,333,359]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" unit="mm" value="0.96">0.96 mm</quantity>
): 0.06:0.23:0.19:0.08: 0.05. Claws on each leg dissimilar, with one apically hooked and one blunt, pad-like (
<figureCitation box="[847,937,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[958,1124,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1139,1211,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Figs 2</figureCitation>
C-D): segment II of forceps subequal in length to segment III, segment II of forceps 1/6 length of segment I; forceps segment I smoothly roundly broadened in basal 1/3 (
<figureCitation box="[509,597,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
); forceps sockets fused, forming a single cavity (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1227,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
); length of styliger plate along median line 1/3 maximum width, posterolateral corners slightly developed; penes widely divided in apical 2/3, apex of each penis lobe with a laterally orientated broad projection (
<figureCitation box="[1003,1074,513,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[197,1391,309,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1391,309,1356]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Bessierus doloris, male imago. A, fore wing; B, tarsal claws; C, genitalia, ventral view; D, genitalia, ventral view, forceps socket, detail." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3460230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3460230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Figs 2</figureCitation>
C-D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="379" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Comments.</emphasis>
Among the diagnostic characteristics of 
<taxonomicName box="[790,897,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[790,897,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Bessierus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(also shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savage" authorityYear="1983" box="[1105,1310,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Perissophlebiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1105,1310,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Perissophlebiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the fused forceps sockets are very unusual. Until recently this has been considered an exclusive characteristic of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulmer. Mariano (2010)" authorityName="Ulmer. Mariano" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Thraulodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1309,1437,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Thraulodes</emphasis>
Ulmer. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mariano, R." box="[238,418,621,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" pagination="129 - 134" refId="ref6993" refString="Mariano, R. (2010) Two new species of Simothraulopsis Traver, 1947 (Ephemeroptera: Leptophlebiidae: Atalophlebiinae) from northeastern Brazil. Aquatic Insects, 32, 129 - 134. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650420903393842" type="journal article" year="2010">Mariano (2010)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
also described this character for two species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Demoulin" authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1966" box="[982,1286,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[982,1164,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Simothraulopsis</emphasis>
Demoulin
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1361,1433,621,647]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. More recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nascimento, J. M. C. &amp; Barcelos-Silva, P. &amp; Salles, F. F." box="[323,597,657,683]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" pagination="191 - 201" refId="ref7038" refString="Nascimento, J. M. C., Barcelos-Silva, P. &amp; Salles, F. F. (2011) Two-winged Leptophlebiidae (Ephemeroptera) from Brazil: new species, records and stage descriptions. Aquatic Insects, 33, 191 - 201. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650424.2011.597408" type="journal article" year="2011">
Nascimento 
<emphasis box="[465,522,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">et al.</emphasis>
(2011)
</bibRefCitation>
, in their revision of this genus, stated the fusion of the forceps socket as a diagnostic character. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E." box="[537,751,693,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref6701" refString="Dominguez, E. (2009) Overview and phylogenetic relationships of the two-winged genera of South American Leptophlebiidae (Ephemeroptera). Aquatic Insects, 31, 63 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650420802518077" type="journal article" year="2009">Domínguez (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulmer. Mariano" authorityYear="2010" box="[761,889,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Thraulodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[761,889,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Thraulodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not closely related neither to 
<taxonomicName box="[1241,1348,694,719]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1241,1348,694,719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Bessierus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savage" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Perissophlebiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Perissophlebiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1966" box="[340,522,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[340,522,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Simothraulopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on the other hand, together with 
<taxonomicName authority="Demoulin" authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1955" box="[894,1177,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Homothraulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[894,1056,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Homothraulus</emphasis>
Demoulin
</taxonomicName>
, was the sister group of 
<emphasis box="[151,345,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Perissophlebiode</emphasis>
s and 
<taxonomicName box="[409,516,766,791]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[409,516,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Bessierus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In that analysis, the adult of 
<taxonomicName box="[843,950,766,791]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Bessierus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[843,950,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Bessierus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Savage" authorityYear="1983" box="[1003,1208,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Perissophlebiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1208,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="379">Perissophlebiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remained unknown, hence it was impossible to know the state of this character.
</paragraph>
